  <!-- 6. FAQ -->
  <section id="faq" class="alt-bg">
    <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

    <div class="faq-list">
      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">What is the H angle in Holdaway analysis?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">The H angle is formed between the H line (from soft tissue Pogonion to the most prominent point of the upper lip) and the NB line (Nasion to bony Pogonion). The norm is approximately 7–15°, with a mean near 10°. A larger angle indicates lip protrusion; a smaller angle indicates retrusion relative to the facial profile.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">What is the difference between the H line and Ricketts' E line?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">The H line runs from soft tissue Pogonion to the most prominent upper lip point. The <a href="/e-line-analysis">Ricketts E line</a> runs from Pronasale (nose tip) to soft tissue Pogonion. Both evaluate lip position, but from different reference frames — the H line is lip-referenced, while the E line is nose-to-chin referenced. Using both together gives a more complete soft tissue picture, particularly where nasal size or chin projection departs from average.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">What is normal upper lip position in Holdaway analysis?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">The upper lip should lie at 0 mm to the H line — that is, exactly on it. A range of −1 to +1 mm is considered within normal limits. Positive values (anterior to the H line) indicate upper lip protrusion; negative values indicate upper lip retrusion. Because the H line is anchored to the upper lip by definition, deviations here are interpreted alongside H angle and lower lip position for the full clinical picture.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">What does skeletal profile convexity tell me in Holdaway analysis?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">Skeletal profile convexity is the linear distance from point A to the NB line, with a norm of approximately 2 mm. It measures the sagittal prominence of the maxillary base relative to the mandible at the hard tissue level — essentially the same construct as ANB angle, expressed linearly. Values above 4 mm suggest a Class II skeletal pattern; negative values suggest a Class III tendency. This measurement provides context for interpreting the H angle and lip position findings.</div>
      </div>
